<section id="docbooktags">
	<title>DocBook Tags</title>
	<para>
		So far you have used a very limited set of
		<wordasword>DocBook</wordasword>
		attributes. The
		following chapter presents more tags which you typically
		need in a
		<wordasword>DocBook</wordasword>
		document.
	</para>
	<section id="docbooktags_text">
		<title>Markup</title>
		<para>
			<table frame='all'>
				<title>Important Docbook tags</title>
				<tgroup cols='2' align='left' colsep='1' rowsep='1'>
					<colspec colname='c1' />
					<colspec colname='c2' />
					<thead>
						<row>
							<entry>Tag</entry>
							<entry>Explanation</entry>
						</row>
					</thead>
					<tbody>
						<row>
							<entry>
								<xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
									parse="text" href="./examples/CDATA" />
							</entry>
							<entry>
								Allows you to enter special signs into the text which would
								be otherwise interpreted by DocBook.
							</entry>
						</row>
						<row>
							<entry>
								<![CDATA[ <programlisting> </programlisting> ]]>
							</entry>
							<entry>
								Highlights the text as coding. You can also specify the
								programming language of this listing, e.g., language="java" or
								language="xml". This
								information can, for example, be used for
								syntax highlighting.
							</entry>
						</row>
						<row>
							<entry>
								<![CDATA[ <wordasword></wordasword> ]]>
							</entry>
							<entry>Indicates a special word</entry>
						</row>
						<row>
							<entry>
								<![CDATA[ <parameter class='command'>/w</parameter> ]]>
							</entry>
							<entry>
								Describes a parameter; <code>class</code> can be command, function,
								option
							</entry>
						</row>
						<row>
							<entry>
								<![CDATA[ <guilabel> </guilabel> ]]>
							</entry>
							<entry>Label on a GUI</entry>
						</row>
						<row>
							<entry>
								<![CDATA[ <guibutton> </guibutton> ]]>
							</entry>
							<entry> Button on a GUI</entry>
						</row>
						<row>
							<entry>
								<![CDATA[ <filename class="directory">/usr/bin</filename>, <filename>db2html</filename> ]]>
							</entry>
							<entry>Directory or filename</entry>
						</row>
						<row>
							<entry>
								<![CDATA[ <emphasis> </emphasis> ]]>
							</entry>
							<entry>Highlights the text</entry>
						</row>
						<row>
							<entry>
								<![CDATA[ <xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" parse="text" href="example1.txt" /> ]]>
							</entry>
							<entry>
								Includes <filename>example1.xml</filename> as text,
								so the file can contain tags, etc.
							</entry>
						</row>
						<row>
							<entry>
								<![CDATA[ <ulink url="http://www.heise.de/newsticker">German IT News</ulink>. ]]>
							</entry>
							<entry>Paste a hypertext link into the document.</entry>
						</row>
						<row>
							<entry>
								<![CDATA[ &amp; ]]>
							</entry>
							<entry>
								Creates the ampersand (&amp;) sign. Can,
								for example, be used in
								links.
							</entry>
						</row>
					</tbody>
				</tgroup>
			</table>
		</para>
	</section>

	<section id="docbooktags_warnings">
		<title>Warnings</title>
		<para>
			To define warning messages, DocBook provides several tags. The
			following list gives an overview of them.
			<itemizedlist>
				<listitem>
					<para>tip</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>note</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>important</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>warning</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>caution</para>
				</listitem>
			</itemizedlist>
		</para>
		<para>The following snippet shows how to use these.</para>
		<para>
			<programlisting language="xml">
				<xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
					parse="text" href="./examples/warning/warning.xml" />
			</programlisting>
		</para>
	</section>

	<section id="docbooktags_linebreak">
		<title>Line break</title>
		<para>
			You
			can create an explicit line break with the <![CDATA[<sbr/> ]]>
			command.
		</para>
	</section>

	<section id="docbooktags_link">
		<title>References to other elements</title>
		<para>
			You link to different elements in Docbook with
			<![CDATA[<xref linkend="id_of_the_element"/> ]]>.
		</para>
	</section>

	<section id="docbooktags_legal">
		<title>Legal Notice</title>
		<para>
			You can define legal notices where you state the conditions
			for reproduction like traditional copyright or an open
			content license. These tags are confined to meta-information.
		</para>
		<para>
			<programlisting language="xml">
				<xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
					parse="text" href="./examples/legalnotice.xml" />
			</programlisting>
		</para>
	</section>

	<section id="docbooktags_index">
		<title>Index</title>
		<para>
			You
			create an index in your document with the <![CDATA[<index/>]]>
			entry.
		</para>
		<para>To create index elements, you can use the following:</para>
		<para>
			<programlisting language="xml">
				<xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
					parse="text" href="./examples/indexelement1.xml" />
			</programlisting>
		</para>
		<para>You can add a secondary index term.</para>
		<para>
			<programlisting language="xml">
				<xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
					parse="text" href="./examples/indexelement2.xml" />
			</programlisting>
		</para>
		<para>You can also place a reference to another index term.</para>
		<para>
			<programlisting language="xml">
				<xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
					parse="text" href="./examples/indexelement3.xml" />
			</programlisting>
		</para>
	</section>

	<section id="docbooktags_table">
		<title>Tables</title>
		<para>You can create a table via the following coding.</para>
		<para>
			<programlisting language="xml">
				<xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
					parse="text" href="./examples/exampletable.xml" />
			</programlisting>
		</para>
	</section>

	<section id="docbooktags_lists">
		<title>Lists</title>
		<para>You can create non-numbered lists like this:</para>
		<para>
			<programlisting language="xml">
				<xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
					parse="text" href="./examples/simplelist.xml" />
			</programlisting>
		</para>

		<para>You can create numbered lists like this:</para>
		<para>
			<programlisting language="xml">
				<xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
					parse="text" href="./examples/numberedlist.xml" />
			</programlisting>
		</para>
	</section>

	<section id="docbooktags_links">
		<title>Links</title>
		<para>You can create links like this</para>

		<programlisting language="xml">
			<xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
				parse="text" href="./examples/link/examplelink.xml" />
		</programlisting>
	</section>

	<section id="docbooktags_graphics">
		<title>Graphics</title>
		<para>
			DocBook has no restrictions what kind of graphic format you
			use,
			e.g.
			JPEG, PNG or SVG.
			You can include graphics via the following
			tag.
			The
			optional
			<parameter>"phrase"</parameter>
			is used in HTML output to define the
			mandatory
			<parameter>"alt"</parameter>
			attribute of image.
		</para>
		<programlisting language="xml">
			<xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
				parse="text" href="./examples/images/images.xml" />
		</programlisting>
		<para>
			You can also specify different graphics for different output
			formats.
		</para>
		<programlisting language="xml">
			<xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
				parse="text" href="./examples/images/images2.xml" />
		</programlisting>
		<para>You can also embed a figure with enumeration and header.</para>
		<programlisting language="xml">
			<xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
				parse="text" href="./examples/images/figure.xml" />
		</programlisting>
	</section>

	<section id="docbooktags_menu">
		<title>Menus</title>
		<para>
			To define menu paths, as, for example,
			<menuchoice>
				<guimenu>File</guimenu>
				<guisubmenu>New Project</guisubmenu>
			</menuchoice>,
			use the following
		</para>
		<programlisting language="xml">
			<xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
				parse="text" href="./examples/gui/menu.xml" />
		</programlisting>
	</section>

